sp.p:
I am the Audience's very humble Servant;
but they cannot make a Man write a Prologue, whether
he can or no.

Sir, I deſire no other Payment but of this ſmall Bill;
your Worſhip's Cattle are ſaddled, and it is a charming Day for
travelling.

Do you think, Madam, this is the very ſame Don—;
what d'ye call him, whom your Father ſaw in Spain, and of
whom he has told us ſuch pure pleaſant Stories?

                        Beau Monde, Sir, is as much as to ſay, a Man of Figure;
when you ſay, he is a Man of the Beau Monde, you
mean juſt ſuch another Perſon as I am.

His Frenzy! his Roguery; the Fellow's a Rogue;
he is no more mad than I am; and the Coachman and Landlord
both have very good Actions at Law againſt him.

A very hopeful Spark this. But he has a great Eſtate;
and I have no Notion of refuſing an Eſtate, let the Man be
what he will.

'Fore George, a good pretty Wench; I'll have a Kiſs;
I'll warrant ſhe's twice as handſom as my Wife, that is to
be.

A Search of Adventures, Sir; no Place abounds more
with them. I was told there was a plenteous Stock of Monſters;
nor have I found one leſs than I expected.
